James Dyson Awards: finalist inventions
A pneumatic gun that fires an emergency buoyancy aid beat a device that uses natural sunlight to make seawater drinkable and an invention that assists paramedics
By David Ferrarotto
3:01PM BST 05 Oct 2010
Comments
One of Britain's most respected designers has called on the Government to do more to encourage young people to embark on an engineering career. Sir James Dyson, the inventor of the world-famous eponymous bagless vacuum cleaner, said: "We produce about 22,000 engineers a year but we have vacancies for 37,000. So we must do a lot to encourage young people to read sciences and design technology at school and then to go on at university to produce the brains and the brilliant ideas that we need to create wealth for our country."
Sir James was speaking exclusively to the Telegraph as the winner of The James Dyson Award 2010 was announced. The annual international design award is run by the James Dyson Foundation, a charitable trust. The inventor added that the Government “must take engineering seriously. When it comes to big infrastructure projects or building submarines or buses the Government should encourage it and early fund it and show industry and universities that engineering matters to this country. It’s a vital part of our economy.”
