Save £1,500 a year by planning meals, says Department of Health
Families could save as much as £1,500 a year and improve their diet simply by planning their weekly food shop better, according to the Department of Health.
By Martin Beckford, Social Affairs Editor
12:01AM GMT 27 Dec 2011
Follow Comments
It found that households bought fewer takeaways, snacked less often and ate more fruit and veg after being given meal-planning advice.
The NHS's healthy lifestyle campaign Change4Life asked 20 households to record what they ate and drank over a fortnight. After the first week the 10 families, five couples and five single people in the survey were given basic tips such as how to write a shopping list and plan meals for the week ahead.
In the second week of the experiment, they saved an average of £29 including spending £15 less on takeaways as well as eating more regular meals and fewer snacks. Over the course of a year this could mean savings of up to £1,508.
The majority (85 per cent) of those who took part said they would continue to plan weekly meals in the future.
Anne Milton, the Public Health Minister, said: “If you're busy and on a budget, you can still eat well. “Some people might think that eating a balanced diet is more expensive but that does not have to be the case. If we plan ahead we can make better choices and save money too. “In the new year we will launch a new Change4Life Supermeals campaign that will help everyone plan and cook simple meals.”
