Internet shame is killing our children
Adolescents aren't emotionally equipped to deal with embarrassment, and when they are exposed online the consequences can be tragic, as the suicide of Daniel Perry shows
Daniel Perry, 17, from Dunfermline, took his own life after being targeted in a web-cam blackmail plot Photo: ENTERPRISE NEWS AND PICTURES	By Jenny McCartney
1:31PM BST 17 Aug 2013
Follow Comments
It can sometimes be difficult, as an adult, to remember the routine intensity of one’s feelings as a teenager. It’s like trying to recall extreme physical pain, or the first insanity of falling in love. Your mind chases after it, remembering the shape of the dent it left in your psyche, but only a trace of it drifts back to you, like a faded scent.
Still, I can recall being much more self-conscious, and at the same time more sarcastic towards others. Teenagers are all too aware that they have a soft, malleable centre – before the trappings of adulthood harden around them – and they grope for things to protect them: sharp words, groups, philosophies, hotly disputed rules of behaviour. One of the things that shielded teenagers when I was growing up, though, was the concept of privacy; every personality needs a patch of shade in which to grow.
We didn’t have email, of course, or texting, camera-phones, Facebook or Twitter or any of the myriad sites such as Ask.fm which seem now to have become fertile grounds for the growth of peer-to-peer cruelty. There was no concept of “sexting”. If you wanted to take a photograph, you had to get out a bulky camera and click. A professional adult developed the film for you, and questions would have been asked if anything untoward had appeared on the prints.
If you did or said something stupid, it was unlikely that anyone would remember it in a fortnight, much less provide concrete evidence. The memory of your mistakes drifted on the air, on gossip and rumour and fallings-outs. The past could disperse like smoke. Within reason, you always had the option of escaping a former version of yourself.
Not any more, and teenagers know it. There was something so intensely sad about the picture last week of Daniel Perry, the 17-year-old Dunfermline boy who killed himself last July after falling prey to blackmailers on Skype. He had such an open, cheerful face, so ready for life’s possibilities.
