Daniel, an apprentice mechanic, had spent much time on Skype talking to someone he believed to be an American girl his own age; it seems he was drawn into some form of sexual indiscretion, as many boys would be. Then the blackmailers revealed themselves, and viciously threatened to make the Skype material (or a manipulated version of it) public unless he deposited money in a named bank account.
The news must have stunned him, and filled him with the fear of being publicly humiliated. He asked them: “What can I do to stop you showing this to my family?”. Then he jumped off the Forth Road Bridge to his death.
There is something uniquely excruciating about the threat of such exposure for teenagers; they are still working out their responses to the opposite sex, treading on delicate ground. At best, their feelings are easily bruised. And for all the obsession of our society with talking about the mechanics of sex, the potential for shame around it, particularly for young people, has not diminished.
Shame can destroy people as surely as poison; it is the most ancient and powerful of emotions. The real shame, of course, should be on those who cruelly or thoughtlessly blast apart the private lives of others. Daniel is not the first to be killed by the threat of private activities being made public. In a much-discussed case in the US, a college freshman called Tyler Clementi jumped off a bridge to his death in 2010 after discovering that his room-mate had set up a webcam in their shared room, and live-streamed footage of Clementi in sexual activity with a boyfriend. Clementi had only recently told his family he was gay.
A 13-year-old London schoolgirl called Chevonea Kendall-Bryan fell to her death from a tower block in 2011 while desperately pleading with a boy to delete a video taken of her in allegedly coerced sexual activity. And a 15-year-old called Audrie Pott in Saratoga, in the US, killed herself in 2012 after three boys allegedly assaulted her when she was drunk and took pictures that they later showed around. Compromising images can now be captured so casually that in some cases adolescent persecutors have deluded themselves into thinking that what they are doing is no big deal: the effect upon their victims, however, is devastating.
The names pile up of teenagers tormented by the circulation – or possible circulation – of images beyond their control. What can adults do? We can try to warn them to confine sexual exploration only to circumstances and people they can fully trust. We can try to rebuild some communal understanding of the rules of privacy, and strengthen them against embarrassment. Still, it feels increasingly like trying to provide a safe map for a minefield.
Daniel’s Twitter account still stands. He talks about liking horses and Big Macs and Chinese food. His description of himself says: “I try not to take life too seriously.” I only wish that part had been true. Wine wisdom starts in your glass
The Government has been so alarmed by levels of middle-class wine drinking, it was reported last week, that it has recommended the definition of “wine” be expanded across the European Union to include low-alcohol and no-alcohol beverages which would not previously have merited the term.
Although France, Spain and Portugal are vigorously opposing the idea, the UK has promised to keep on pursuing it, in what a government spokesman called the “best long-term interests” of consumers (by which he means, I imagine, a reduction in damage to the beleaguered internal organs of enthusiastic British tipplers).
The renaming of wine, however, smacks of desperation. In my childhood, those adults who wanted wine on special occasions drank it, and those who didn’t – but wanted to look celebratory – happily drank fizzy grape juice in a wine glass.
But now, it seems, British professionals, in particular (statistically, the most tireless wine drinkers) have got into the habit of cracking open a bottle at “wine o’clock” most evenings, and carrying on merrily until bedtime. Their idea seems to be that wine-drinking doesn’t count as proper, damaging drinking, but is more of a kind of benevolent liquid homage to a European lifestyle. Doctors beg to differ.
Yet, rather than tampering with the integrity of wine, why not simply return glasses to the modest size they once were before those giant fish bowls on glass stalks grew popular in the Nineties, and a “glass” came to mean a quarter of a litre? Nutritionists are always saying that the one sure way to limit food intake painlessly is simply to eat from a smaller plate. I have a feeling that much the same applies to drink. Protest? Throw the other one
I hope that Ed Miliband’s dry-cleaner has an arsenal of efficient stain removers: the Labour leader’s suit was splattered with egg once again last week, as he toured a London street market (the last time it took a hit was in Southampton last May). To his credit, he maintained his sangfroid, shrugged off his jacket and continued with the walkabout, while the egg-thrower – whom I deliberately will not name – gave an interview to the BBC about his reasons for attacking the Labour leader.
They were predictably vague: he didn’t “believe” Mr Miliband; he was angry about “weapons of mass deception”; the poor are seen as “a burden”. Still, fair enough: so why not write a letter, vote, hold up a placard, join a protest, start a petition, stand for political office? Ruining someone’s jacket with uncooked omelette seems an odd way to promote change.
But I then don’t think that egg-throwers are really concerned with change: for all its overtones of popular, medieval protest, a fiercely flung egg in a democracy is just a nasty little form of self-righteous assault. Such actions are a reminder that the alternative to having MPs who plod through the slow detail of constituency meetings and committees is missile-chucking mob rule: when I see a politician with egg on his or her face, my respect for the job soars.
